                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">labourer, Robert-street, Mill-wall, Poplar.</hi> I was in bed on the morning of the 18th of March, and heard money jingle on the floor—I awoke, and found the prisoner by the side of my bed, with my jacket in his hand, and the money falling out—2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. fell out on the floor—he gave me 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he said, "This is my money"—I said, "It is not"—I got up, and the two shillings were gone—more men slept in the room, but they were gone—I had no time to send for an officer then, but gave him in charge at dinner time the same day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> He was your bed-fellow, was he not? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; his clothes were on the top of the bed, and mine at the side—I had 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in my pocket at first, but after I had 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in silver, and some halfpence in my coat pocket—he did not shake my waistcoat pocket and hold it up to me—he asked what money I had in my pocket—I said 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and then some money fell, and he said 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. of it was his.</p>
